{{Infobox person | name = Philippe A. Autexier | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | birth_name = Philippe Alexandre Autexier<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://catalogue.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/cb11889608x |title=Autexier, Philippe Alexandre |website=[[BnF]] |accessdate=2018-02-16 |language=fr}}</ref> | birth_date = {{birth year|1954}} | birth_place = [[Châtellerault]], [[France]] | death_date = {{death year and age|1998|1954}} | death_place = [[Poitiers]], [[France]] | residence = | nationality = French | education = | alma_mater = | occupation = [[Music historian]] | years_active = | employer = | organization = | agent = | known_for = | notable_works = | style = | home_town = | television = | religion = <!-- Religion should be supported with a citation from a reliable source --> | spouse = | children = | awards = | signature = | website = <!-- {{URL|Example.com}} --> | footnotes = }}
'''Philippe Alexandre Autexier''' (1954–1998) was a French [[music historian]], [[musicologist]], journalist and [[Masonic]] researcher, whose research on [[Mozart]] and other Masonic composers is particularly significant.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.netzwerk-freimaurerforschung.de/blog/wordpress/?page_id=105 |title=Zwei Arbeiten aus dem Nachlass Philippe Autexier |website=Netzwerk Freimaurerforschung |accessdate=2018-02-16 |language=de}}</ref>
== Biography == Autexier was passionate about music, his research led him to become a musicologist and music historian, a speaker who expressed in [[French language|French]], [[English language|English]], [[German language|German]] and [[Italian language|Italian]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.editionsdetradavs.com/contents/fr/d3_Autexier_Philippe.html |title=Autexier, Philippe : Biographie |website=Éditions Detrad |accessdate=2018-02-16 |language=fr}}</ref> He has taught at several [[Music school|conservatories]] and universities in France, Italy, Germany, United Kingdom and the United States. He has written music reviews for various specialised journals, and a number of books on [[Mozart]], [[Liszt]], [[Bartók]] and other [[Freemason]] musicians. He was director of the “{{lang|fr|Mozart et franc maçon|italic=no}}” (Mozart and Freemason) exhibition in 1991 in [[Cahors]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ina.fr/video/TLC9109251804 |title=Exposition Mozart et franc maçon à Cahors |website=[[ina.fr]] |accessdate=2018-02-16 |language=fr}}</ref> He has also participated in many radio programmes, such as [[France Musique]], [[France Culture]], [[BBC Radio]], as well as [[Germany|German]] and [[Swiss]] channels.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.decitre.fr/livres/beethoven-9782070394234.html |title=Beethoven - La force de l'absolu : À propos de l'auteur |website={{ill|Decitre|fr}} |accessdate=2018-02-16 |language=fr}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.babelio.com/auteur/Philippe-Alexandre-Autexier/188749 |title=Philippe Alexandre Autexier |website=Babelio |accessdate=2018-02-16 |language=fr}}</ref>
During more than 20 years, he worked on the subject of “{{lang|fr|Colonne d’Harmonie}}” (Column of Harmony)—a research on the [[Masonic music]] history—which led him to study all the collections of Masonic archives in Europe ([[Paris]], [[Strasbourg]], [[Zürich]], [[Vienna]], [[Bayreuth]], [[Berlin]], [[Poznań]], [[The Hague]], et cetera). The research results have been published in his book {{lang|fr|La Colonne d’Harmonie : Histoire, Théorie, Pratique|italic=yes}}.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.detrad.com/contents/fr/p3181_La_Colonne_d_Harmonie_-_Philippe_Autexier.html |title=La Colonne d'Harmonie - Philippe Autexier |website=detrad.com |accessdate=2018-02-16 |language=fr}}</ref>
Among Autexier’s publications, the only work for the general public is {{lang|fr|Beethoven : La force de l’absolu|italic=yes}}, which is a heavily illustrated [[Pocket edition|pocket book]] belonging to the [[Collection (publishing)|collection]] “[[Découvertes Gallimard]]” and has been translated into seven languages, including English. It is simple, concise and accessible to all, unlike the rest of his books which are elitist.
== Bibliography == * ''Béla Bartók : Musique de la vie'', Stock Musique, 1981 * ''Les oeuvres témoins de Mozart'', Éditions A. Leduc, 1982 * ''Mozart & Liszt sub Rosa'', Centre Mozart, 1984 * ''Mozart'', Honoré Champion, 1987 * ''Don Giovanni : Horizons mozartiens'', Philippe Olivier, 1990 * ''Beethoven : La force de l’absolu'', collection « [[Découvertes Gallimard]] » (nº 106), série Arts. Éditions Gallimard, 1991, new edition in 2010<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.gallimard.fr/Catalogue/GALLIMARD/Decouvertes-Gallimard/Decouvertes-Gallimard/Arts/Beethoven |title=''Beethoven : La force de l’absolu'', collection Découvertes Gallimard (n° 106) |publisher=[[Éditions Gallimard]] |accessdate=2018-02-16}}</ref> ** ''Beethoven: The Composer as Hero'', “[[Abrams Discoveries]]” series. Harry N. Abrams, 1992. (U.S. edition) ** ''Beethoven: The Composer as Hero'', ‘[[New Horizons (Thames & Hudson)|New Horizons]]’ series, Thames & Hudson, 1992. (UK edition) * ''La Lyre Maçonne : Mozart, Haydn, Spohr, Liszt'', Éditions Detrad aVs, 1991 * ''La Colonne d’Harmonie : Histoire, Théorie, Pratique'', Éditions Detrad aVs, 1991, new edition in 2013 * ''L’art de la planche : Théorie et pratique du morceau d’architecture et de la communication en loge'', Éditions Detrad aVs, 1996, new edition in 2005
